<BLOCK1><TI TOCID="I">NOTICE OF APPEAL</TI>
<P>THE APPLICANT (APPELLANT) THE COMMONWELL MUTUAL INSURANCE GROUP (&ldquo;COMMONWELL&rdquo;) APPEALS to the Court of Appeal from the judgment of the Honourable Mr. Justice MacLeod dated October 4, 2018, in the Ontario Superior Court of Justice at Ottawa.</P>
<P>THE APPELLANT ASKS that the judgment be set aside and judgement be granted as follows:</P>
<P>1. Granting a declaration that the appellant is not obliged to defend or indemnify the Respondent in Ontario Superior Court of Justice action No. 15-64061 commenced in Ottawa (&ldquo;the Action&rdquo;);</P>
<P>2. Costs payable to Commonwell; and</P>
<P>3. Such further and other relief as counsel for Commonwell may request and that this Honourable Court considers just.</P>
<P>THE GROUNDS OF APPEAL are as follows:</P>
<P>1. Commonwell appeals a decision of the Superior Court of Justice <EM>per</EM> Justice MacLeod dated October 4, 2018 wherein the Applicant's (Appellant's) application was dismissed.</P>
<P>2. Commonwell provided liability coverage to the respondent from February 14, 2013 to February 14, 2014 pursuant to a residential insurance policy no. XXXXXXXXXX (the &ldquo;Policy&rdquo;).</P>
<P>3. The Respondent seeks a defence and indemnity from Commonwell in the Action. Commonwell brought an Application for a declaration that it was not obliged to defend or indemnify the Respondent.</P>
<P>4. The Statement of Claim in the Action alleges that the Respondent was negligent in the operation of a 2001 Honda R4C off road dirt bike owned by another (the &ldquo;dirt bike&rdquo;), causing personal injury to the plaintiff.</P>
<P>5. Commonwell states that the allegations made in the Statement of Claim of the Action are not covered by the Policy. Specifically, the Policy did not cover the operation of the dirt bike.</P>
<P>6. His Honour hearing the Application did not determine whether the Policy covered the dirt bike. Instead, he held that regardless of whether the Policy provided coverage, Commonwell had either waived its rights or was estopped from denying coverage.</P>
<P>7. It is respectfully submitted that the Learned Judge hearing the Application erred in law and fact by:
<P1>(a) Providing inadequate reasons for the decision;</P1>
<P1>(b) Finding that the Action had proceeded to discoveries when the first inquiries were made as to coverage issues, when in fact, inquiries were made a preliminary stage and not in the context of oral discoveries;</P1>
<P1>(c) Incorrectly articulating Commonwell's position with respect to consent, finding that Commonwell took the position that Mr, Campbell did not have consent, when in fact, it was Commonwell's position that the issue of consent was a live one on the pleadings, thereby giving rise to a duty of defend. Rather, Commonwell took the position that if at trial it is found that there is no consent there may be no duty to indemnify under the Policy;</P1>
<P1>(d) Finding that Commonwell could not rely on the issue of consent given that a reservation of rights was not provided, when the evidence regarding when the issue of consent was raised was not discussed at the hearing and there was insufficient evidence filed with respect to same;</P1>
<P1>(e) Failing to determine whether the Policy provided coverage for the allegations made in the Action, and specifically, that the Policy did not provide coverage for same;</P1>
<P1>(f) Failing to distinguish between waiver and estoppel in his reasons;</P1>
<P1>(g) Inappropriately applying the case law wherein insurers have been found to have estopped themselves by defending a claim through production, discovery and settlement negotiations without a reservation of rights. His Honour failed to distinguish between those cases and the matter at hand where coverage became an issue at a very early stage in the action;</P1>
<P1>(h) Applying the doctrine of estoppel without finding any detrimental reliance on the part of the Respondent;</P1>
<P1>(i) <CASEREF><SOC>Misapplying Economical Insurance Group v. Fleming</SOC><YEAR>2008</YEAR><CITE>89 OR (3D) 68</CITE></CASEREF> and other law to find waiver without finding that there was any express waiver in writing;</P1>
<P1>(j) Failing to consider the requirements of the <EM>Insurance Act</EM> R.S.O. 1990, c.I.8 and specifically section 131(1) which requires waiver to be in writing;</P1>
<P1>(k) Failing to consider the Policy wording which required waiver to be in writing; and</P1>
<P1>(l) Such further and other grounds as counsel may advise and this Honourable Court permit.</P1></P>
<P>THE BASIS OF THE APPELLATE COURT'S JURISDICTION IS:</P>
<P>1. The decision of His Honour Justice MacLeod is final;</P>
<P>2. Section 6(l)(b) of the <EM>Courts of Justice Act</EM>, R.S.O. 1990, c. C.43, as amended; and</P>
<P>3. Rule 61 of the <EM>Rules of Civil Procedure</EM>.</P>
<P>November 2, 2018</P>
