<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="I">PART I&mdash;STATEMENT</TI>
<P>1. The Appellant, The Commonwell Mutual Insurance Group (&ldquo;Commonwell&rdquo;), appeals the judgment of the Honourable Justice MacLeod dated October 4, 2018 in the Ontario Superior Court of Justice at Ottawa.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="II">PART II&mdash;OVERVIEW</TI>
<P>2. Commonwell is an Ontario insurer which at all material times provided liability coverage to the responding party, Shayne Campbell (&ldquo;the respondent&rdquo;) pursuant to a residential insurance policy no. XXXXXXXXXX effective from February 14, 2013 to February 14, 2014 (the &ldquo;Policy&rdquo;).
<P1><BOLD><EM>Affidavit of Iain Convery</EM>, sworn August 2, 2016 <EM>(&ldquo;Convery Affidavit&rdquo;)</EM> at Exhibits B and C, Exhibit Book at tabs 1B and 1C, pp. 21&ndash;65; Appeal Book and Compendium at tab 6, p. 26.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>3. The Respondent seeks a defence and indemnity from Commonwell in Ontario Superior Court of Justice Action number 15-64061 commenced in Ottawa (the &ldquo;Action&rdquo;). Commonwell brought an Application for a declaration that it was not obliged to defend or indemnify the Respondent.</P>
<P>4. The Honourable Justice hearing the Application held that regardless of whether the Policy provided coverage, Commonwell had either waived its rights or was estopped from denying coverage. It was also held that the Respondent was entitled to defence and indemnity.</P>
<P>5. Commonwell states that the issues are as follows:
<P1>(a) Were the reasons given for the decision adequate?</P1>
<P1>(b) Is the Respondent entitled to both defence and indemnity?</P1>
<P1>(c) Does waiver apply?</P1>
<P1>(d) Does estoppel apply?</P1></P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="III">PART III&mdash;FACTS</TI>
<P>6. The Statement of Claim in the Action alleges that the Respondent was negligent in the operation of a 2001 Honda R4C off road dirt bike owned by another individual (the &ldquo;Dirt Bike&rdquo;), causing personal injury to the plaintiff.
<P1><BOLD><EM>Convery Affidavit</EM> at Exhibit A, Exhibit Book at tab 1A, pp. 6&ndash;20; Appeal Book and Compendium at tab 6, p. 26.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>7. Commonwell states that the allegations made in the Statement of Claim of the Action are not covered by the Policy. Specifically, the Policy did not cover the operation of the Dirt Bike.</P>
<P>8. With some exceptions, the Policy generally excludes liability coverage for the use or operation of any motorized vehicle. The Policy will provide liability coverage for the use or operation of a self-propelled land vehicle that the Respondent does not own, provided that the vehicle does not need to be registered under any government authority.</P>
<P>9. The Policy wording provided details of the liability coverage at Section 2&mdash;Coverage E. The relevant sections of the policy are as follows:
<QUOTE><BLOCK2 LABEL="Coverage"><N>E</N><TI>LEGAL LIABILITY</TI>
<P>&ldquo;We&rdquo; will pay all sums which &ldquo;you&rdquo; become legally liable to pay as compensatory damages because of &ldquo;bodily injury&rdquo; or &ldquo;property damage&rdquo;.</P>
<P>The amount of insurance is the maximum amount &ldquo;we&rdquo; will pay under one or more Sections of Coverage E, for all the compensatory damages in respect of one accident or occurrence other than as provided under Defense, Settlement, Supplementary Payments.</P>
<P>&ldquo;You&rdquo; are insured for claims made against &ldquo;you&rdquo; arising from:</P>
<P>1. <BOLD>Personal Liability</BOLD>&mdash;&ldquo;legal liability&rdquo; arising out of &ldquo;your&rdquo; personal actions anywhere in the world.</P>
<P>&ldquo;You&rdquo; are not insured for claims made against &ldquo;you&rdquo; arising from:</P>
<P>(a) the ownership, use or operation of any motorized vehicle, trailer or watercraft, except those for which coverage is shown in this policy;</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI>SPECIAL LIMITATIONS</TI>
<BLOCK3><TI>Motorized Vehicles</TI>
<P><BOLD>Vehicles You Do Not Own:</BOLD> &ldquo;You&rdquo; are insured against claims arising out of &ldquo;your&rdquo; use or operation of any self-propelled land vehicle, amphibious vehicle or air cushion vehicle, including their trailers which &ldquo;you&rdquo; do not own, provided that:</P>
<P>1. the vehicle is not required to be registered under any government authority and it is designed primarily for use off public roads;</P></BLOCK3></BLOCK2></QUOTE>
<P1><BOLD><EM>Convery Affidavit</EM> at para. 7, Exhibit Book at tab 1, p. 2; Appeal Book and Compendium at tab 6, pp. 27-28.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>10. The Dirt Bike is both a motor vehicle within the meaning of the <EM>Highway Traffic Act</EM>, R.S.O. 1990, c. H.8 (the &ldquo;<EM>HTA</EM>&rdquo;) and an off-road vehicle within the meaning of the <EM>Off-Road Vehicles Act</EM>, RSO 1990, c O.4 (the &ldquo;<EM>OVA</EM>&rdquo;). It is required to be registered.
<P1><BOLD><EM>Highway Traffic Act</EM>, R.S.O. 1990, c. H.8, ss. 1(1) and 7(1) [<EM>HTA</EM>], Book of Authorities of the Appellant at Tabs B1 and B2.</BOLD></P1>
<P1><BOLD><EM>Off-Road Vehicles Act</EM>, R.S.O. 1990, c. O.4, s. 1 [<EM>OVA</EM>], Book of Authorities of the Appellant at Tab B5.</BOLD></P1>
<P1><BOLD><EM>Operation of Off-Road Vehicles on Highways</EM>, O. Reg. 316/03, s. 16, Book of Authorities of the Appellant at Tab B6.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>11. Given that the Dirt Bike was required to be registered, the Policy excludes coverage for the use or operation of the Dirt Bike. The Applicant therefore takes the position that it does not owe a duty to defend and indemnify the Respondent in the Action.</P>
<P>12. The Respondent reported the accident when he was served with the Statement of Claim in May, 2015.
<P1><BOLD><EM>Convery Affidavit</EM> at para. 11, Exhibit Book at tab 1, p. 4; Appeal Book and Compendium at tab 6, p. 29.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>13. In or about June, 2015, the Appellant appointed counsel to defend the Respondent in the action and a Statement of Defence and Crossclaim and Jury Notice were served and filed on his behalf.
<P1><BOLD><EM>Convery Affidavit</EM> at para. 12 and Exhibit E, Exhibit Book at tab 1, pp. 4 and 68&ndash;81; Appeal Book and Compendium at tab 6, p. 29.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>14. In or around January, 2016, Ms. Morel was asked by counsel for the plaintiff to advise if there were any coverage issues. This inquiry was passed to Commonwell. Commonwell obtained a coverage opinion.
<P1><BOLD><EM>Convery Affidavit</EM> at paras. 13-14 and Eshibit E, Exhibit Book at tab 1, pp. 5 and 68&ndash;81; Appeal Book and Compendium at tab 6, p. 30.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>15. Commonwell wrote to the Respondent on March 7, 2016 advising that there was no coverage under the Policy and that the within Application would be brought for a declaration that there was no duty to defend or indemnify him in the action.
<P1><BOLD><EM>Convery Affidavit</EM> at para 15 and Exhibit F, Exhibit Book at tab 1, pp. 5 and 82&ndash;85; Appeal Book and Compendium at tab 6, p. 30.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>16. At the time that coverage was denied, pleadings had been exchanged in the Action. However, affidavits of documents had not been exchanged and examinations for discoveries had not yet been conducted.
<P1><BOLD><EM>Affidavit of Pamela J. Dummy, sworn</EM> January 18, 2018 (&ldquo;<EM>Duminy Affidavit</EM>&rdquo;) at Exhibit A, Exhibit Book at tab 3A, pp. 249&ndash;251; Appeal Book and Compendium at tab 8, p. 41.</BOLD></P1></P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="IV">PART IV&mdash;ISSUES, LAW AND SUBMISSIONS</TI>
<P>17. Commonwell states that the issues are as follows:
<P1>(a) Were the reasons given for the decision adequate?
<P2>(i) Should there have been a finding that there was no coverage?</P2>
<P2>(ii) Should there have been a distinction between waiver and estoppel?</P2></P1>
<P1>(b) Is the Respondent entitled to both defence and indemnity?</P1>
<P1>(c) Does waiver apply?</P1>
<P1>(d) Does estoppel apply?</P1></P>
<BLOCK3><N>(a)</N><TI>Were the reasons given for the decision adequate?</TI>
<BLOCK4><N>(i)</N><TI>Should there have been a finding that there was no coverage?</TI>
<P>18. In His Honour's reasons, he states that &ldquo;it seems highly probable that at the moment of the accident, the Dirt Bike was a vehicle that required registration&rdquo;. However, there is no finding as to whether there is coverage for the Dirt Bike in question. Ultimately, His Honour states that he &ldquo;might well have found that the operation of an unregistered vehicle on a roadway or highway fell within the exclusionary language&rdquo; but did not do so because it was found that the Appellant was bound to provide coverage due to waiver and estoppel.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>The Commonwell Mutual Assurance Group v. Campbell</SOC><CITE>2018 ONSC 5899</CITE><PARANUM>27-28</PARANUM><CORRELAT><CITE>298 A.C.W.S. (3d) 163</CITE></CORRELAT></CASEREF><BOLD>, Appeal Book and Compendium at tab 3, pp. 14-15.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>19. The Appellant respectfully submits that if the Policy provides coverage, the issues of waiver and estoppel are irrelevant as there is a duty to defend and indemnify. The issues of waiver and estoppel only arise if there is no duty to defend or indemnify pursuant to the Policy.</P>
<P>20. The Appellant submits that in this case, the Policy does not provide coverage and accordingly, there is no duty to defend or indemnify.</P>
<P>21. The duty to defend is broader than the duty to indemnify in that it is triggered when there is a mere possibility that the claim, if successful, would require the insurer to indemnify the insured. There is no duty to defend if the claim clearly falls outside the scope of coverage.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Nichols v. American Home Assurance Co.</SOC><CITE>[1990] 1 S.C.R. 801</CITE><PARANUM>16-17</PARANUM><CORRELAT><CITE>72 O.R. (2d) 799</CITE></CORRELAT></CASEREF><BOLD>, Book of Authorities of the Appellant at Tab A7.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>22. Determining whether or not an insurer has a duty to indemnify is a three-step process. Specifically:
<P1>(a) First, the court must determine if the plaintiff's legal allegations are properly pleaded. That is, the court must decide the true nature of the claims. In this case, the Plaintiffs' claim in the Action is a claim for personal injuries sustained in a motor vehicle accident, allegedly caused in whole or in part by the negligence of the Respondent. The claim is based in the tort of negligence.</P1>
<P1>(b) Second, the court must determine if any claims are entirely derivative in nature. There are no derivative claims in the subject Action.</P1>
<P1>(c) Third, the court must determine if any of the properly pleaded, non-derivative claims could trigger an insurer's duty to defend.</P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Non-Marine Underwriters, Lloyd's of London v. Scalera</SOC><CITE>2000 SCC 24</CITE><PARANUM>50&ndash;52</PARANUM><CORRELAT><CITE>[2000] 1 S.C.R. 551</CITE></CORRELAT></CASEREF> <BOLD>[<EM>Scalera</EM>], Book of Authorities of the Appellant at Tab A8.</BOLD></P1>
<P1><BOLD><EM>Convery Affidavit</EM> at Exhibit A, Exhibit Book at tab 1A, pp. 6&ndash;20; Appeal Book and Compendium at tab 6, p. 26.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>23. When the language of the policy is unambiguous, the court should give effect to the clear language, reading the contract as a whole. Where the language of a policy is ambiguous, the court should prefer interpretations that are consistent with the reasonable expectations of the parties.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Progressive Homes Ltd. v. Lombard General Insurance Co. of Canada</SOC><CITE>2010 SCC 33</CITE><PARANUM>15 and 22-23</PARANUM><CORRELAT><CITE>[2010] 2 S.C.R. 245</CITE></CORRELAT></CASEREF> <BOLD>[<EM>Progressive Homes</EM>], Book of Authorities of the Appellant at Tab A9.</BOLD></P1>
<P1><BOLD><EM>Scalera</EM>, <EM>supra</EM> para. 22 at para. 71, <EM>Book</EM> of Authorities of the Appellant at Tab A8.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>24. Any remaining ambiguities shall be interpreted against the insurer, pursuant to the <EM>contra proferentem</EM> rule. This generally means that coverage should be construed broadly and exclusion clauses narrowly.
<P1><BOLD><EM>Progressive Homes</EM>, <EM>supra</EM> para. 23 at para. 23, Book of Authorities of the Appellant at Tab A9.</BOLD></P1>
<P1><BOLD><EM>Scalera</EM>, <EM>supra</EM> para. 22 at para. 70, <EM>Book</EM> of Authorities of the Appellant at Tab A8.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>25. The language of the subject Policy is unambiguous. Therefore, the court should give effect to the clear language.</P>
<P>26. The initial grant of coverage is subject to exclusion clauses. The Policy excludes claims arising from the ownership, use or operation of any motorized vehicle, trailer or watercraft.
<P1><BOLD><EM>Convery Affidavit</EM> at para. 7, <EM>Exhibit</EM> Book at tab 1, p. 2; Appeal Book and Compendium at tab 6, pp. 27-28.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>27. In <CASEREF><SOC>Silverthorne v. Gore Mutual Insurance Co.</SOC></CASEREF>, the Ontario Court of Appeal considered an exclusion clause identical to that within the subject Policy and found no ambiguity in the word &ldquo;use&rdquo;. The phrase &ldquo;ownership, use or operation&rdquo; within this exclusion clause has been interpreted to require some element of control in relation to the vehicle by the insured.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Silverthorne v Gore Mutual Insurance Co.</SOC><YEAR>2001</YEAR><CITE>52 O.R. (3d) 560</CITE><PARANUM>14 and 20</PARANUM><CORRELAT><CITE>200 D.L.R. (4th) 378</CITE></CORRELAT><COURTJUR>Ont. C.A.</COURTJUR></CASEREF> <BOLD>[<EM>Silverthorne</EM>], Book of Authorities of the Appellant at Tab A15.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>28. The allegations against the Respondent as set out in paragraph 19 of the Plaintiffs' Statement of Claim arise out of the Respondent's use and operation of the subject Dirt Bike. The allegations in the Statement of Claim are clearly related to the Respondent's alleged control over the vehicle within the meaning of the exclusion clause.
<P1><BOLD><EM>Convery Affidavit</EM> at Exhibit A, Exhibit Book at tab 1A, pp. 6&ndash;20; Appeal Book and Compendium at tab 6, p. 26.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>29. The Policy does not explicitly define &ldquo;motorized vehicle&rdquo; to include a Dirt Bike. In <CASEREF><SOC>Red River Valley Mutual Insurance Co. v. Rockola</SOC></CASEREF> [<EM>Rockola</EM>], the Manitoba Court of Queen's Bench considered an exclusion clause identical to that within the subject Policy. It concluded that the exclusion clause would apply to the operation of a Dirt Bike, unless the insured qualified for one of the exceptions to the exclusion clause. It was accepted that the Dirt Bike was a &ldquo;motorized vehicle&rdquo; pursuant to the exclusion clause.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Red River Valley Mutual Insurance Co. v Rockola</SOC><YEAR>1993</YEAR><CITE>90 Man. R. (2d) 46</CITE><PARANUM>10</PARANUM><CORRELAT><CITE>43 A.C.W.S. (3d) 994</CITE></CORRELAT><COURTJUR>Man. Q.B.</COURTJUR></CASEREF> <BOLD>[<EM>Rockola</EM>], aff'd</BOLD> <CASEREF><YEAR>1994</YEAR><CITE>92 Man. R. (2d) 298</CITE><CORRELAT><CITE>47 A.C.W.S. (3d) 619</CITE></CORRELAT><COURTJUR>Man. C.A.</COURTJUR></CASEREF><BOLD>, Book of Authorities of the Appellant at Tab A10.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>30. The Respondent admitted on cross-examination that the Dirt Bike was motorized.
<P1><BOLD>The Transcript of the Cross Examination of Shayne Campbell at p. 38, Line 25 and p. 39, lines 1-2, Exhibit Book at tab 4, pp. 301-302; Appeal Book <EM>and</EM> Compendium at tab 5, pp. 24-25.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>31. Accordingly, it is the Applicant's position that the Plaintiff's claim arises from the Respondent's use and operation of a motorized vehicle. The Action therefore falls under the exclusion clause.</P>
<P>32. The exclusion clause is subject to exceptions, which would bring an excluded claim back within coverage. One such exception is claims arising from the insured's use or operation of any self-propelled land vehicle that is not owned by the insured. However, the exception only applies if certain conditions are satisfied. One of these conditions is that the vehicle is not required to be registered under any government authority.
<P1><BOLD><EM>Convery Affidavit</EM> at para. 7, Exhibit Book at tab 1, p. 2; Appeal Book and Compendium at tab 6, p. 26.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>33. A similar, albeit arguably more narrow exception and condition was considered in <EM>Rockola</EM>. In that case, the policy required the vehicle to be &ldquo;not subject to motor vehicle registration.&rdquo; Manitoba legislation defined a Dirt Bike as an off-road vehicle, which was subject to registration under their <EM>Off-Road Vehicles Act</EM> but not their <EM>Highway Traffic Act</EM>. Based on this, the insured claimed that there was a distinction between motor vehicles and off-road vehicles, such that the phrase &ldquo;motor vehicle registration&rdquo; in the policy did not include off-road vehicle registration.
<P1><BOLD><EM>Rockola</EM>, <EM>supra</EM> para 29 at paras. 10, 17, and 25, Book of Authorities of the Appellant at Tab A10.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>34. The Manitoba Court of Queen's Bench disagreed. It held that a Dirt Bike was propelled by an internal combustion engine and was a motor vehicle. The fact that registration was under the <EM>Off-Road Vehicles Act</EM> did not turn the Dirt Bike into something other than a motor vehicle, in the ordinary sense of that word. It concluded that the phrase &ldquo;motor vehicle registration&rdquo; encompassed vehicles subject to registration under both the <EM>Highway Traffic Act</EM> and the <EM>Off-Road Vehicles Act</EM>. The claim was therefore excluded from coverage, which decision was upheld on appeal by the Manitoba Court of Appeal.
<P1><BOLD><EM>Rockola</EM>, <EM>supra</EM> para 29 at paras. 21, 26, and 35, Book of Authorities of the Appellant at Tab A10.</BOLD></P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Red River Valley Mutual Insurance Co. v Rockola</SOC><YEAR>1994</YEAR><CITE>92 Man R (2d) 298</CITE><CORRELAT><CITE>47 A.C.W.S. (3d) 619</CITE></CORRELAT><COURTJUR>Man. C.A.</COURTJUR></CASEREF><BOLD>, aff'g <EM>Rockola</EM>, <EM>supra</EM> para 29, Book of Authorities of the Appellant at Tab A11.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>35. In this case, the exception refers to registration under any government authority, not simply motor vehicle registration.</P>
<P>36. Under Ontario legislation, a Dirt Bike is both a motor vehicle and an off-road vehicle. If operated on a highway, it is required to be registered under the <EM>HTA</EM>. Pursuant to the wording of the subject Policy, the Dirt Bike is required to be registered under a government authority. Therefore, the condition is unsatisfied, the exception does not apply and the claim is excluded from coverage.</P>
<P>37. The <EM>HTA</EM> defines &ldquo;motor vehicle&rdquo; as:
<QUOTE><P>an automobile, a motorcycle, a motor assisted bicycle unless otherwise indicated in this Act, and any other vehicle propelled or driven otherwise than by muscular power, but does not include a street car or other motor vehicle running only upon rails, a power-assisted bicycle, a motorized snow vehicle, a traction engine, a farm tractor, a self-propelled implement of husbandry or a road-building machine;</P></QUOTE>
<P1><BOLD><EM>HTA</EM>, <EM>supra</EM> para. 10 at s. 1(1), Book of Authorities of the Appellant at Tab B1.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>38. The Dirt Bike is propelled by a motorized engine, not muscular power. It falls under the category of &ldquo;any other vehicle propelled or driven otherwise than by muscular power.&rdquo; It does not fall within the list of exceptions to that general category. The Dirt Bike is clearly a motor vehicle.</P>
<P>39. As a motor vehicle, the Dirt Bike was required to have a valid permit if it was operated on a highway, pursuant to section 7(1) of the <EM>HTA</EM>.
<P1><BOLD><EM>HTA</EM>, <EM>supra</EM> para. 10 at s. 7(1), Book of Authorities of the Appellant at Tab B2.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>40. The term &ldquo;highway&rdquo; is defined in the <EM>HTA</EM> to include:
<QUOTE><P>a common and public highway, street, avenue, parkway, driveway, square, place, bridge, viaduct or trestle, any part of which is intended for or used by the general public for the passage of vehicles and includes the area between the lateral property lines thereof;</P></QUOTE>
<P1><BOLD><EM>HTA</EM>, <EM>supra</EM> para. 10 at s. 1(1), Book of Authorities of the Appellant at Tab B1.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>41. The Dirt Bike was operated on Ridge Road. The Respondent admitted on cross-examination that Ridge Road was used by cars. The Applicant takes the position that Ridge Road was therefore a highway within the meaning of the <EM>HTA</EM> because it was a street used by the general public for the passage of vehicles.
<P1><BOLD>The Transcript of the Cross Examination of Shayne Campbell at p. 39, lines 6&ndash;8, Exhibit Book at tab 4, p. 302; Appeal Book and Compendium at tab 5, p. 25.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>42. As a motor vehicle operated on a highway, section 7(1) of the <EM>HTA</EM> creates a registration requirement for the Dirt Bike. The exception to the exclusion clause cannot apply because one of the necessary conditions is unfulfilled. The Plaintiffs' claim therefore falls under the exclusion clause.</P>
<P>43. The Dirt Bike can also be an off-road vehicle. For the purposes of the <EM>HTA</EM> and pursuant to section 191.8 (5) of that Act, an &ldquo;off-road vehicle&rdquo; means an off-road vehicle within the meaning of the <EM>OVA</EM>, which defines &ldquo;off-road vehicle&rdquo; as:
<QUOTE><P>a vehicle propelled or driven otherwise than by muscular power or wind and designed to travel,</P>
<P>(a) on not more than three wheels, or</P>
<P>(b) on more than three wheels and being of a prescribed class of vehicle;</P></QUOTE>
<P1><BOLD><EM>HTA</EM>, <EM>supra</EM> para. 10 at s. 191.8(5), Book of Authorities of the Appellant at Tab B3.</BOLD></P1>
<P1><BOLD><EM>OVA</EM>, <EM>supra</EM> para. 10 at s. 1, Book of Authorities of the Appellant at Tab B5.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>44. The Dirt Bike has two wheels. It is motorized and is neither propelled by muscular power or wind. It is therefore also an off-road vehicle within the meaning of the <EM>OVA</EM> and the <EM>HTA</EM>.
<P1><BOLD><EM>Convery Affidavit</EM> at Exhibit D, Exhibit Book at tab 1D, pp. 66-67; Appeal Book and Compendium at tab 6, p. 26.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>45. Section 191.8(1) of the <EM>HTA</EM> provides that no person shall drive an off-road vehicle on a highway except in accordance with the regulations and any applicable municipal by-laws.
<P1><BOLD><EM>HTA</EM>, <EM>supra</EM> para. 10 at s. 191.8(1), Book of Authorities of the Appellant at Tab B3.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>46. Section 16 of the <EM>Operation of Off-road Vehicles on Highways</EM>, a regulation enacted under the authority of the <EM>HTA</EM>, provides:
<QUOTE><P>16 (1) The off-road vehicle shall not be operated on a highway unless a permit under section 5 of the <EM>Off-Road Vehicles Act</EM> has been issued in respect of that vehicle and a number plate showing the number of the permit is displayed on the vehicle as required under that Act.</P>
<P>(1) Subsection (1) does not apply to an off-road vehicle operated under the authority of a permit issued under section 7 of the <EM>Highway Traffic Act</EM>, as provided by section 7 of the <EM>Off-Road Vehicles Act</EM>.</P></QUOTE>
<P1><BOLD><EM>Operation of Off-Road Vehicles</EM>, <EM>supra</EM> para. 10 at s. 16, Book of Authorities of the Appellant at Tab B6.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>47. As an off-road vehicle operated on a highway, this regulation creates a registration requirement for the Dirt Bike. Again, the exception to the exclusion clause cannot apply because one of the necessary conditions is unfulfilled. The Plaintiffs' claim therefore falls under the exclusion clause.</P></BLOCK4>
<BLOCK4><N>(ii)</N><TI>Should there have been a distinction between waiver and estoppel?</TI>
<P>48. It is respectfully submitted that His Honour erred in not distinguishing between waiver and estoppel in the Reasons for Decision.</P>
<P>49. At the outset of the Reasons, it is stated that Commonwell is &ldquo;estopped from denying coverage&rdquo;. Ultimately, however, His Honour held that &ldquo;either waiver or estoppel will apply&rdquo;.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>The Commonwell Mutual Assurance Group v. Campbell</SOC><CITE>2018 ONSC 5899</CITE><PARANUM>2 and 42</PARANUM><CORRELAT><CITE>298 A.C.W.S. (3d) 163</CITE></CORRELAT></CASEREF><BOLD>, Appeal Book and Compendium at tab 3, pp. 10 and 17.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>50. Commonwell submits that the Reasons do not distinguish between waiver and estoppel and as articulated further below, that these are separate and distinct legal doctrines that must be applied separately.</P></BLOCK4></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><N>(b)</N><TI>Is the Respondent entitled to both defence and indemnity?</TI>
<P>51. His Honour's reasons state that Commonwell took the position that Mr. Campbell did not have consent to operate the Dirt Bike. Commonwell respectfully submits that the issue of consent was a live one on the pleadings in the Action, and states that through its counsel, it admitted that if there was otherwise coverage on the policy, this would give rise to a duty to defend, but depending on the outcome at trial, may not lead to a duty to indemnify. There were no submissions made at the hearing regarding when the issue of consent first arose.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>The Commonwell Mutual Assurance Group v. Campbell</SOC><CITE>2018 ONSC 5899</CITE><PARANUM>25</PARANUM><CORRELAT><CITE>298 A.C.W.S. (3d) 163</CITE></CORRELAT></CASEREF><BOLD>, Appeal Book and Compendium at tab 3, p. 14.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>52. Commonwell submits that while it was open for his Honour to find that there was a duty to defend, there was insufficient evidence available for His Honour to find a duty to indemnify.</P>
<P>53. Depending on the findings at trial, it may be that there is no duty to indemnify for reasons other than those raised at the hearing of the Application. These would be new issues that may need to be litigated separately.</P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><N>(c)</N><TI>Does Waiver Apply?</TI>
<P>54. Commonwell submits that waiver cannot apply because there was no finding of an express waiver in writing.</P>
<P>55. The test for waiver requires evidence that the party waiving had:
<P1>(a) A full knowledge of its rights; and</P1>
<P1>(b) An unequivocal and conscious intention to abandon them.</P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Saskatchewan River Bungalows Ltd. v. Maritime Life Assurance Co.</SOC><CITE>[1994] 2 S.C.R. 490</CITE><PARANUM>20</PARANUM><CORRELAT><CITE>155 A.R. 321</CITE></CORRELAT></CASEREF> <BOLD>[<EM>Saskatchewan River</EM>], Book of Authorities of the Appellant at Tab A14.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>56. In <EM>Saskatchewan River</EM>, the Supreme Court of Canada noted that no consideration moves from the party in whose favour a waiver operates. An overly broad interpretation of waiver would undermine the requirement of contractual consideration.
<P1><BOLD><EM>Saskatchewan River</EM>, <EM>supra</EM> para. 55 at para. 20, Book of Authorities of the Appellant at Tab A14.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>57. During the relevant time between May, 2015, when the Respondent was served with the Statement of Claim in the Action and March 7, 2016 when the Applicant denied coverage, section 131(1) of the <EM>Insurance Act</EM> R.S.O. 1990, c. I. 8, section 131(1) specifically provided that no term or condition of a contract shall be deemed to be waived by the insurer in whole or in part unless the waiver was stated in writing and signed by a person authorized for that purpose by the insurer. This section was only repealed and replaced on July 1, 2016, after the within Application was issued.
<P1><BOLD><EM>Insurance Act</EM>, R.S.O. 1990, c. I.8, s. 131(1), Book of Authorities of the Appellant at Tab B4.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>58. It is notable that the Policy is a contract. Its terms and conditions also speak to waiver. It states at Section 10 of the Additional Conditions that Commonwell &ldquo;shall not be deemed to have waived any term or condition of this policy in whole or in part, unless [the] waiver is clearly stated and in writing, and is signed by a person authorized to do so&rdquo;...
<P1><BOLD><EM>Convery Affidavit</EM> at <EM>Exhibit</EM> C, Exhibit Book at tab 1C, pp. 24&ndash;65; Appeal Book and Compendium at tab 6, p. 26.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>59. The Reasons for Decision rely on <CASEREF><SOC>Economical Insurance Group v. Fleming</SOC><YEAR>2008</YEAR><CITE>89 OR (3d) 68</CITE></CASEREF> (&ldquo;Economical&rdquo;). Commonwell submits that in Economical it was found that there was a written waiver. In this case, the Reasons for Decision make no finding that there was a written waiver by the Appellant and signed by an authorized person.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Economical Insurance Group v. Fleming</SOC><YEAR>2008</YEAR><CITE>89 O.R. (3d) 68</CITE><CORRELAT><CITE>163 A.C.W.S. (3d) 1021</CITE></CORRELAT><COURTJUR>Ont. Sup. Ct.</COURTJUR></CASEREF> <BOLD>[<EM>Economical</EM>], aff'd</BOLD> <CASEREF><CITE>2009 ONCA 112</CITE><CORRELAT><CITE>[2009] O.J. No. 456</CITE></CORRELAT></CASEREF><BOLD>, Book of Authorities of the Appellant at Tab A3.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>60. Commonwell submits that waiver must be clear and unambiguous and that the Court has found in the past, that simply retaining counsel for an insured, even if a Notice of Intent to Defend or Statement of Defence is filed, is insufficient to establish waiver.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Djepic v. Kuburovic</SOC><YEAR>2005</YEAR><CITE>136 A.C.W.S. (3d) 112</CITE><PARANUM>30</PARANUM><CORRELAT><CITE>[2005] OJ. No. 374</CITE></CORRELAT><COURTJUR>Ont. Sup. Ct.</COURTJUR><CASEHIST><CASEDISP>rev'd on other grounds</CASEDISP><CASEREF><YEAR>2006</YEAR><CITE>80 O.R. (3d) 21</CITE><CORRELAT><CITE>263 D.L.R. (4th) 709</CITE></CORRELAT><COURTJUR>Ont. C.A.</COURTJUR></CASEREF></CASEHIST></CASEREF><BOLD>, Book of Authorities of the Appellant at Tab A1.</BOLD></P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>ING Insurance Co. of Canada v. Miracle</SOC><CITE>2010 ONSC 4056</CITE><PARANUM>31</PARANUM><CORRELAT><CITE>[2010] O.J. No. 3778</CITE></CORRELAT></CASEREF> <BOLD>[<EM>ING Insurance</EM>], rev'd on other grounds</BOLD> <CASEREF><CITE>2011 ONCA 321</CITE><CORRELAT><CITE>105 O.R. (3d) 241</CITE></CORRELAT></CASEREF><BOLD>, Book of Authorities of the Appellant at Tab A5.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>61. Commonwell respectfully submits that the conditions for waiver have not been met.</P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><N>(d)</N><TI>Does Estoppel Apply?</TI>
<P>62. His Honour held that the Action had proceeded to discoveries when the first inquiries were made as to coverage issues. The Appellant respectfully submits that this is an overly broad interpretation of &ldquo;discovery&rdquo; for the case at issue. At the time that coverage was denied, pleadings had been exchanged in the Action. However, affidavits of documents had not been exchanged and examinations for discoveries had not yet been conducted.
<P1><BOLD><EM>Duminy Affidavit</EM> at Exhibit A, Exhibit Book at tab 3A, pp. 249&ndash;251; Appeal Book and Compendium at tab 8, p. 41.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>63. At the hearing of the Application, the Respondent relied on <CASEREF><SOC>Rosenblood Estate v. Law Society of Upper Canada</SOC></CASEREF> to argue that estoppel applied. In that decision, the Court found that for estoppel to apply,
<P1>(a) there must be knowledge on the part of the insurer of the facts which indicated a lack of coverage; and</P1>
<P1>(b) there must be a course of conduct by the insurer upon which the insured relied to its detriment.</P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Economical Insurance Group v. Fleming</SOC><YEAR>2008</YEAR><CITE>89 O.R. (3d) 68</CITE><CORRELAT><CITE>163 A.C.W.S. (3d) 1021</CITE></CORRELAT><COURTJUR>Ont. Sup. Ct.</COURTJUR></CASEREF> <BOLD>[<EM>Economical</EM>], aff'd</BOLD> <CASEREF><CITE>2009 ONCA 112</CITE><CORRELAT><CITE>[2009] O.J. No. 456</CITE></CORRELAT></CASEREF><BOLD>, Book of Authorities of the Appellant at Tab A3.</BOLD></P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Rosenblood Estate v. Law Society of Upper Canada</SOC><CITE>[1989] O.J. No. 240</CITE><PARANUM>53-54</PARANUM><CORRELAT><CITE>14 A.C.W.S. (3d) 85</CITE></CORRELAT><COURTJUR>Ont. S.C.</COURTJUR></CASEREF> <BOLD>[<EM>Rosenblood</EM>], aff'd</BOLD> <CASEREF><CITE>[1992] O.J. No. 3030</CITE><COURTJUR>Ont. C.A.</COURTJUR></CASEREF> <BOLD>at paras. 53-54,</BOLD> <CASEREF><CITE>37 A.C.W.S. (3d) 534</CITE></CASEREF><BOLD>, Book of Authorities of the Appellant at Tab A2.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>64. In <EM>Rosenblood</EM>, the Court found that prejudice will be presumed where an insurer persists in defending an action through production of documents, examinations for discovery and settlement negotiations.
<P1><BOLD><EM>Rosenblood</EM>, <EM>supra</EM> para. 63 at para. 63, Book of Authorities of the Appellant at Tab A12.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>65. This case is distinguishable from situations where a defence was provided through discovery and settlement negotiations. The Appellant submits that the issue of coverage was communicated to the Respondent early in the litigation, a legal Application was initiated and that the Respondent had the benefit of independent legal counsel almost since the outset of the underlying litigation. Accordingly, it submits that prejudice cannot be presumed.</P>
<P>66. The Respondent did not provide any evidence of actual prejudice in this case and none was found in the Reasons for Decision.</P>
<P>67. Commonwell respectfully submits that estoppel does not apply because there was no detrimental reliance found on the part of the Respondent.</P></BLOCK3></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="V">PART V&mdash;RELIEF SOUGHT</TI>
<P>68. Commonwell respectfully requests that this Court set aside the judgment of the Ontario Superior Court of Justice and that judgment be granted as follows:
<P1>(a) Granting a declaration that the Appellant is not obliged to defend or indemnify the Action;</P1>
<P1>(b) Costs payable to Peel Mutual; and</P1>
<P1>(c) Such further and other relief as counsel for Commonwell may request and that this Honourable Court considers just.</P1></P>
<P>ALL OF WHICH IS RESPECTFULLY SUBMITTED THIS 12<SUP>th</SUP> DAY OF FEBRUARY, 2019.</P>
