<BLOCK1><TI>FACTUM OF THE RESPONDENT</TI>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="I">PART I&mdash;<UNDER>OVERVIEW STATEMENT</UNDER></TI>
<P>1. At all material times, the Respondent, Shayne Campbell (&ldquo;Campbell&rdquo;), was insured under a policy of insurance with the Appellant, The Commonwell Mutual Assurance Group (&ldquo;Commonwell&rdquo;).</P>
<P>2. On April 28, 2013, Campbell was involved in an accident while he was riding a dirt bike. As a result of that accident, Evan Rodger (the &ldquo;Plaintiff&rdquo;) issued a Statement of Claim in Ottawa as Court File No. 15-65061 (the &ldquo;Claim&rdquo;), naming Campbell as a Defendant, and served Campbell with the Statement of Claim in April 2015.</P>
<P>3. Campbell advised Commonwell of the Claim. In June 2015, Commonwell appointed counsel to defend Campbell in the Claim and pleadings were served on Campbell's behalf.</P>
<P>4. Commonwell did not serve a reservation of rights letter nor did Campbell sign a non-waiver agreement. In fact, no issue as to coverage was raised at all.</P>
<P>5. Notwithstanding the above, during the course of litigation, Commonwell informed Campbell that it would no longer cover the Claim relying solely on facts that were plain and obvious in the Plaintiff's Statement of Claim.</P>
<P>6. Commonwell brought an application seeking a declaration that it was not obliged to defend or indemnify Campbell, which application was heard May 29, 2018.</P>
<P>7. In his decision of October 4, 2018, Justice MacLeod held that Commonwell both waived its right to deny coverage and was also estopped from doing so. As such, Campbell was entitled to a defence and to be indemnified by Commonwell.</P>
<P>8. Commonwell appeals this decision.</P>
<P>9. Campbell states that Justice MacLeod had a full appreciation of the facts when undertaking his analysis of whether Commonwell owed Campbell a duty to defend and indemnification.</P>
<P>10. Commonwell has failed to demonstrate that Justice MacLeod made any palpable and overriding error with regards to facts or inferences from same, or that he was incorrect on questions of law. In the circumstances, there is no basis upon which to overturn the decision of Justice MacLeod and this appeal ought to be dismissed with costs to Campbell.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="II">PART II&mdash;<UNDER>STATEMENT OF FACTS</UNDER></TI>
<P>11. Campbell accepts as correct the facts found at paragraphs 6, 8, 9, 13, 14, and 15 of Commonwell's Factum.</P>
<P>12. Campbell disagrees with the facts found at paragraphs 7, 10, 11, 12, and 16 of Commonwell's Factum.</P>
<P>13. In April 2015, Campbell was served with a Statement of Claim in which he was named as a defendant, upon receipt of which he immediately advised Commonwell, his home insurer, and Guarantee Company of North America (&ldquo;Guarantee&rdquo;), his auto insurer.
<P1><BOLD><EM>Affidavit of Shayne Campbell</EM>, sworn April 24, 2017 (&ldquo;<EM>Campbell Affidavit</EM>&rdquo;) at paras. 2, 13 and Exhibits A and D, Exhibit Book of the Appellant at Tabs 2, 2A, 2D, pp. 87 and 90, 95&ndash;109 and 216&ndash;223; Respondent's Compendium at Tabs 1, 2, 3, pp. 2 and 5, 10&ndash;24 and 25&ndash;32.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>14. Paragraph 6 of the Statement of Claim states:
<QUOTE><P>The Defendant, Shayne Campbell (&ldquo;Campbell&rdquo;) is an individual residing in the Township of Champlain, in the County of Prescott-Russell, Ontario. At all material times, Campbell was the operator of a Red 2001 Honda R4C off road dirt bike owned by the Defendants John William Russell and/or RCOMM Radio Inc. as described in Ontario Motor Vehicle Accident Report Accident Number 3513-00234 (hereinafter referred to as the &ldquo;Red Honda&rdquo;).</P></QUOTE>
<P1><BOLD><EM>Campbell Affidavit</EM> at Exhibit A, Exhibit Book of the Appellant at Tab 2A, p. 101; Respondent's Compendium at Tab 2, p. 16.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>15. In June 2015, Commonwell appointed Louise Morel (&ldquo;Morel&rdquo;) to defend the Claim on Campbell's behalf.
<P1><BOLD><EM>Campbell Affidavit</EM> at para. 14 and Exhibit E, Exhibit Book of the Appellant at Tabs 2, 2E, pp. 90-91, 224&ndash;237; Respondent's Compendium at Tabs 1, 4, pp. 5&ndash;6, 33&ndash;46.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>16. Also, in June 2015, Guarantee's adjuster met with Campbell to take a statement. Thereafter, Guarantee asked Campbell to sign a Non-Waiver agreement and subsequently sent a Reservation of Rights letter.
<P1><BOLD><EM>Campbell Affidavit</EM> at para. 13 and Exhibit D, Exhibit Book of the Appellant at Tabs 2, 2D, pp. 90-91, 216&ndash;223; Respondent's Compendium at Tabs 1, 3, pp. 5-6, 25&ndash;32.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>17. In July 2015, Campbell then met with Commonwell's adjuster, who also took a statement. The statement includes the following:
<QUOTE><P>I took John's red Honda XR400 dirt bike-it's a 2001. The bike isn't insured for the road that I was aware of. It's very basic-it's strictly off road. There aren't any mirrors or turn signals or a plate.</P></QUOTE>
<P1><BOLD><EM>Affidavit of Pamela J. Duminy</EM>, sworn January 18, 2018 (&ldquo;<EM>Duminy Affidavit</EM>&rdquo;) and Exhibit B, Exhibit Book of the Appellant at Tabs 3, 3B, pp. 246&ndash;248, 253; Respondent's Compendium at Tabs 6, 8, pp. 50&ndash;52, 57.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>18. Commonwell did not send a reservation of rights letter nor a non-waiver agreement as no issue as to coverage was ever raised. Instead, on August 17, 2015, Morel filed a Statement of Defence, Crossclaim, and Jury Notice. The Statement of Defence alleges as follows at paragraphs 4 and 5:
<QUOTE><P>4. Campbell...was operating the red 2001 Honda R4C off-road dirt bike...owned by the Defendants... in full conformity with all of the laws and regulations relating to the use and operation of motorized and off-road vehicles....</P>
<P>5. ...he was travelling westbound on Ridge Road...</P></QUOTE>
<P1><BOLD><EM>Campbell Affidavit</EM> at para. 14 and Exhibit E, Exhibit Book of the Appellant at Tabs 2, 2E, pp. 91, 226; Respondent's Compendium at Tabs 1, 4, pp. 6, 35.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>19. There was no suggestion that the defence was restricted or qualified in any way.</P>
<P>20. On March 7, 2016, Commonwell wrote to Campbell stating that the Claim would no longer be covered because the Policy contained an exclusion. Specifically, the denial letter states:
<QUOTE><P>In the statement of claim the plaintiffs allege that you were negligent in the operation of a red 2001 Honda R4C off road dirt bike....causing personal injury.</P>
<P>You are insured... provided that the vehicle is not required to be registered...</P>
<P>The 2001 Honda R4C off road dirt bike... was required to be registered...</P>
<P>Accordingly, there is no coverage...Commonwell will be bringing an Application.</P></QUOTE>
<P1><BOLD><EM>Campbell Affidavit</EM> at para. 19 and Exhibit H, Exhibit Book of the Appellant at Tabs 2, 2H pp. 92, 243&ndash;245; Respondent's Compendium at Tabs 1, 5, pp. 7, 47&ndash;49.</BOLD></P1>
<P1><BOLD><EM>Affidavit of Iain Convery</EM>, sworn August 2, 2016 at para. 13 and Exhibit F, Exhibit Book of the Appellant at Tabs 1, 1F, pp. 5, 82&ndash;85; Respondent's Compendium at Tabs 9, 10, pp. 72, 74&ndash;76.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>21. The Application was launched in August 2016 and was not heard until May 29, 2018. By the time of hearing, pleadings had been exchanged in the underlying Claim and all parties had been examined for discovery. A timetable was set requiring the matter to have been mediated by December 15, 2017.
<P1><BOLD>Transcript of Cross Examination of Shayne Campbell, dated November 8, 2017, Exhibit Book of the Appellant at Tab 4, pp. 264-304; Respondent's Compendium at Tab 11, p. 77&ndash;117.</BOLD></P1>
<P1><BOLD><EM>Duminy Affidavit</EM> at Exhibit A, Exhibit Book of the Appellant at Tab 3A, pp. 249&ndash;251; Respondent's Compendium at Tab 7, p. 53&ndash;55.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>22. Campbell will suffer prejudice if Commonwell is allowed to now withdraw from coverage.
<P1><BOLD><EM>Campbell Affidavit</EM> at para. 20, Exhibit Book of the Appellant at Tab 2, p. 92; Respondent's Compendium at Tab 1, p. 7.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>23. In his Reasons for Judgment, Justice MacLeod concluded that Commonwell owed Campbell a duty to defend and an obligation to indemnify on the following basis:
<P1>a) Commonwell retained Morel as counsel to defend the action and a detailed statement of defence was delivered;</P1>
<P1>b) All the facts on which Commonwell now purports to rely to deny coverage were readily apparent at the time this was done;</P1>
<P1>c) Campbell was never told of any issue with coverage, he was never asked to sign a non-waiver, and he was never given a reservation of rights letter;</P1>
<P1>d) At the time the statement of defence was filed, Campbell was aware of these documents as he had been provided these documents by his auto insurer, Guarantee. Campbell understood that Morel was his lawyer and that Commonwell was defending him. Campbell relied upon these facts and did not follow up with his own counsel or Guarantee;</P1>
<P1>e) Commonwell only wrote to Campbell to advise there was no coverage once litigation was well advanced;</P1>
<P1>f) It would have been unfair to allow Commonwell to abandon Campbell at that stage and it is too late for Commonwell to deny coverage;</P1>
<P1>g) Prejudice may be presumed where the insurer persisted in the defence of the claim;</P1>
<P1>h) Either waiver or estoppel would apply to prevent Commonwell from denying coverage.</P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>The Commonwell Mutual Assurance Group v. Campbell</SOC><CITE>2019 ONSC 5899</CITE><CORRELAT><CITE>298 A.C.W.S. (3d) 163</CITE></CORRELAT></CASEREF><BOLD>, Respondent's Compendium at Tab 12, pp. 118&ndash;126.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>24. Justice MacLeod correctly concluded that Commonwell either waived or was estopped from denying a defence and indemnification to Campbell. Justice MacLeod fully appreciated the facts and applied the proper tests in a manner consistent with the case law in arriving at this decision.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="III">PART III&mdash;<UNDER>CAMPBELL'S POSITION RE: COMMONWELL'S ISSUES</UNDER></TI>
<P>25. Commonwell states that the issues are as follows:
<P1>a) Were the reasons given for the decision adequate?</P1>
<P1>b) Is the Respondent entitled to both defence and indemnity?</P1>
<P1>c) Does waiver apply?</P1>
<P1>d) Does estoppel apply?</P1></P>
<BLOCK3><N><EM>A</EM>.</N><TI><EM>Were the reasons given for the decision adequate</EM>?</TI>
<P>26. Inadequacy of reasons is not a stand-alone basis for appeal, as was confirmed by Justice Rothstein in <CASEREF><SOC>C. (R.) v McDougall</SOC></CASEREF>. Notwithstanding, the reasons given by Justice MacLeod for his decision were adequate. If a judge's reasons reveal the path the judge took to reach a conclusion on the matter in dispute, the reasons are adequate for the purposes of appellate review.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>C. (R.) v. McDougall</SOC><CITE>2008 SCC 53</CITE><PARANUM>97</PARANUM><CORRELAT><CITE>[2008] 3 S.C.R. 41</CITE></CORRELAT></CASEREF> <BOLD>[<EM>McDougall</EM>], Respondent's Book of Authorities (&ldquo;RBOA&rdquo;) at Tab A1.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>27. Commonwell's Notice of Application states that the Application is for &ldquo;A declaration and Order that it is not obligated to provide a defence or indemnity to the respondent in Ontario Superior Court of Justice action no. 15-64061 commenced in Ottawa (&ldquo;the Action&rdquo;).&rdquo; Commonwell was not seeking a declaration that the allegations contained in the Action fell within the exclusionary language of the Policy.
<P1><BOLD>Notice of Application issued March 11, 2016; Appeal Book and Compendium of the Appellant at Tab 4, p. 21.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>28. Justice MacLeod states at paragraphs 27 and 28 of his decision the following:
<QUOTE><P>The application of the exclusion in the policy is not as clear as it may seem because of complexity in the interaction between the <EM>ORVA</EM>, Part X.3 of the <EM>HTA</EM> and various regulations and municipal by-laws which may provide exemptions permitting off-road vehicles to travel on the road.... Had circumstances been different, I might well have found that the operation of an unregistered vehicle on a roadway or highway fell within the exc lusionary language. I am unable to do so in this case because I have concluded that in the absence of a reservation of right, CMAG is obliged to provide coverage.</P></QUOTE>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>The Commonwell Mutual Assurance Group v. Campbell</SOC><CITE>2019 ONSC 5899</CITE><PARANUM>27-28</PARANUM><CORRELAT><CITE>298 A.C.W.S. (3d) 163</CITE></CORRELAT></CASEREF><BOLD>, Respondent's Compendium at Tab 12, p. 122-123.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>29. After reviewing the law regarding waiver and estoppel, and applying those principles to the facts of the case, Justice MacLeod declared that Commonwell was obligated to provide a defence and to indemnify Campbell, in direct response to the request under the Notice of Application.</P>
<P>30. A judge is under a duty to provide adequate reasons. However, as recognized by the Supreme Court of Canada in <CASEREF><SOC>R v Walker</SOC></CASEREF>, such reasons will be sufficient &ldquo;if they are responsive to the case's live issues and to the parties.&rdquo; An appeal court cannot intervene simply because it believes that the trial judge did a poor job of expressing himself.
<P1><BOLD><EM>McDougall</EM>, <EM>supra</EM> para. 26 at para. 99, RBOA at Tab A1.</BOLD></P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>R v. Walker</SOC><CITE>2008 SCC 34</CITE><PARANUM>20</PARANUM><CORRELAT><CITE>[2008] 2 S.C.R. 245</CITE></CORRELAT></CASEREF><BOLD>, RBOA at Tab A2.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>31. With regards to the applicability of the exclusion, Campbell states as follows. The Policy provides coverage to Campbell for vehicles he does not own provided that &ldquo;the vehicle is not required to be registered under any government authority and it is designed primarily for use off public roads.&rdquo; The clause is not ambiguous. No evidence has been tendered to suggest that when not on public roads, the Dirt Bike was required to be registered. Campbell provided a statement that the Dirt Bike was &ldquo;strictly off road&rdquo;. It is only if the dirt bike is operated on a highway, is it required to be registered under the HTA, and even then, as noted by Justice MacLeod, exceptions arise.
<P1><BOLD>Policy wording, Exhibit Book of the Appellant at Tab 1C, p. 50.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>32. For Commonwell's argument to be effective, the provision would have to be interpreted as &ldquo;not required to be registered <UNDER>under any circumstances</UNDER>.&rdquo; By Commonwell's logic then, there would be no coverage to Campbell had the accident occurred on private property. As such, the exclusion does not apply.</P>
<P>33. Justice MacLeod recognized same at paragraph 27 when he states, &ldquo;Unless it was being used solely on the owner's property, or fell under another exemption, it would have required a licence plate under the <EM>ORVA</EM>.... Nevertheless, it seems highly probable that <BOLD>at the moment of the accident</BOLD>, the dirt bike was a vehicle that required registration.&rdquo;
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>The Commonwell Mutual Assurance Group v. Campbell</SOC><CITE>2019 ONSC 5899</CITE><PARANUM>27</PARANUM><CORRELAT><CITE>298 A.C.W.S. (3d) 163</CITE></CORRELAT></CASEREF><BOLD>, Respondent's Compendium at Tab 12, p. 122.</BOLD></P1></P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><N><EM>B</EM>.</N><TI><EM>Is the Respondent entitled to both defence and indemnity</EM>?</TI>
<P>34. Justice MacLeod determined that Commonwell has waived its right and is estopped from denying coverage. It therefore flows that where coverage cannot be denied, the insurer must indemnify.</P>
<P>35. At a minimum, Commonwell is precluded from taking the position that it is not required to indemnify Campbell under the Policy for lack of consent or any applicable exclusion clause(s). With regards to consent, at no time has Commonwell advised Campbell that coverage may be denied on the basis of lack of consent and as such, is estopped from doing so for purposes of denying indemnification. As stated by Justice MacLeod at paragraph 26, &ldquo;In my view [Commonwell] could not have refused to defend the action based on lack of consent but it could have provided a defence under a reservation of rights. Of course, it did not do so.&rdquo; For Commonwell's argument to be effective, the provision would have to be interpreted as &ldquo;not required to be registered, <UNDER>under any circumstances</UNDER>&rdquo;. By Commonwell's logic then, there would be no coverage to Campbell had the accident occurred on private property.</P>
<P>36. As was the case in <CASEREF><SOC>Snair v Halifax Insurance Nationale-Nederlanden North America Corp.</SOC></CASEREF>, Commonwell should be estopped from denying indemnification because of its course of conduct.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Snair v. Halifax Insurance Nationale-Nederlanden North America Corp.</SOC><CITE>1995 CarswellNS 80</CITE><PARANUM>64&ndash;67, 75</PARANUM><COURTJUR>NSSC</COURTJUR><CASEHIST><CASEREF><CITE>[1995] N.S.J. No. 424</CITE></CASEREF></CASEHIST></CASEREF> <BOLD>[<EM>Snair</EM>], RBOA at Tab A3.</BOLD></P1></P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><N><EM>C</EM>.</N><TI><EM>Does Waiver Apply</EM>?</TI>
<P>37. The doctrine of waiver prevents insurers from denying coverage after they have already started to defend the action on their insured's behalf. This doctrine requires no evidence of prejudice or detriment. Rather, Courts will apply the waiver doctrine if the following criteria are met:
<P1>(i) the insurer knew that its duty to defend and indemnify had not become operative because of a condition of the contract;</P1>
<P1>(ii) the insurer, nonetheless, took actions to defend the insured; and</P1>
<P1>(iii) the insurer did not enter into a non-waiver agreement with or issue a reservation of rights letter to the insurer.</P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Economical Insurance Group v. Fleming</SOC><CITE>2008 CarswellOnt 26</CITE><PARANUM>31&ndash;34</PARANUM><COURTJUR>Ont. Sup. Ct.</COURTJUR><CASEHIST><CASEREF><CITE>163 A.C.W.S. (3d) 1021</CITE></CASEREF></CASEHIST></CASEREF> <BOLD>[<EM>Economical</EM>], aff'd</BOLD> <CASEREF><CITE>2009 ONCA 112</CITE></CASEREF><BOLD>, RBOA at Tab A4.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>38. Justice MacLeod notes the following with regards to waiver:
<P1>a) Where a breach has been waived, the insurer cannot later resile from such waiver (para 30);</P1>
<P1>b) Where a claim clearly falls outside the scope of insurance policy or falls within an exclusion or exception, the insurer should deny coverage clearly and unequivocally (para 31);</P1>
<P1>c) An insurer that proceeds to defend an action, or even an insurer which unequivocally states that it will defend an action, may be taken to have waived reliance on the exclusion or it may be estopped from later denying coverage (para 32);</P1>
<P1>d) If the facts as pleaded clearly give rise to an exclusion and the insurer ignores it and proceeds to defend the action it may be deemed to have waived its right to rely on the exclusion (para 34).</P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>The Commonwell Mutual Assurance Group v. Campbell</SOC><CITE>2019 ONSC 5899</CITE><PARANUM>30&ndash;32, 34</PARANUM><CORRELAT><CITE>298 A.C.W.S. (3d) 163</CITE></CORRELAT></CASEREF><BOLD>, Respondent's Compendium at Tab 12, p. 123.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>39. Commonwell's actions in light of the factual matrix, amounts to a waiver of its right to deny coverage, as its conduct met all three criteria for this doctrine.</P>
<P>40. Commonwell's carriage of the defence in the absence of a non-waiver agreement or reservation of rights letter constitutes a representation by conduct and amounts to a waiver of any right to deny coverage. The Court will infer that the insurer intentionally elected to relinquish its right to treat its obligation to defend as at an end and rather, it elected to treat its obligation as subsisting. That election, once made and communicated to the insured, is irrevocable.
<P1><BOLD><EM>Economical</EM>, <EM>supra</EM> para. 37 at paras 31&ndash;34, RBOA at Tab A4.</BOLD></P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Western Canada Accident &amp; Guarantee Insurance Co. v. Parrott</SOC><CITE>1921 CarswellSask 81</CITE><PARANUM>49&ndash;51</PARANUM><COURTJUR>SCC</COURTJUR><CASEHIST><CASEREF><CITE>59 D.L.R. 507</CITE></CASEREF></CASEHIST></CASEREF> <BOLD>[<EM>Western</EM>], RBOA at Tab A5.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>41. There can be no doubt that Commonwell and its representatives had full knowledge of its rights under the Policy. It is, after all, an insurer and its business is assessing claims and determining whether they are covered by the policies of insurance it has issued.</P>
<P>42. On August 14, 2015 Commonwell filed a statement of defence on behalf of Campbell. That was the equivalent of stating, in writing, &ldquo;We elect to defend&rdquo;.</P>
<P>43. As Justice Holland wrote in <CASEREF><SOC>Rosenblood Estate v. Law Society of Upper Canada</SOC></CASEREF>:
<QUOTE><P>When a claim is presented to an insurer the facts giving rise to the claim should be investigated. If there is no coverage then the insured should be told at once and the insurer should have nothing further to do with the claim if it wishes to maintain its off-coverage position. If coverage is questionable the insurer should advise the insured at once and in the absence of a non -waiver agreement or of an adequate reservation of rights letter defends the claim at its risk. In the present case the insurer finally took an off-coverage position but... much too late.</P></QUOTE>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Rosenblood Estate v. Law Society of Upper Canada</SOC><CITE>1989 CarswellOnt 642</CITE><PARANUM>64</PARANUM><COURTJUR>Ont. Sup. Ct.</COURTJUR><CASEHIST><CASEREF><CITE>[1989] O.J. No. 240</CITE></CASEREF></CASEHIST></CASEREF> <BOLD>[<EM>Rosenblood</EM>], aff'd</BOLD> <CASEREF><CITE>[1992] O.J. No. 3030</CITE><COURTJUR>Ont. C.A.</COURTJUR></CASEREF><BOLD>, RBOA at Tab A6.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>44. The failure of Commonwell to take an off-coverage position and to continue to do so as the litigation ensued, was a continuing election that amounted to a waiver by conduct. Campbell need not prove prejudice in the case of waiver, but in any event, as Justice Holland noted in Rosenblood Estate, prejudice must be presumed where the insurer persisted in the defence through productions and discovery.
<P1><BOLD><EM>Rosenblood</EM>, <EM>supra</EM> para. 43 at para. 63, RBOA at Tab A6.</BOLD></P1></P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><N><EM>D</EM>.</N><TI><EM>Does Estoppel Apply</EM>?</TI>
<P>45. Justice MacLeod at paragraph 36 of his decision clearly states that the principles of estoppel and waiver are distinct, stating, &ldquo;Quite apart from election or waiver, an insurer that provides a defence to the insured without a reservation of rights may be estopped from taking an off coverage position later in the litigation&rdquo;, and turned his mind to the analysis of estoppel discussed in the Court of Appeal case of Rosenblood.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>The Commonwell Mutual Assurance Group v. Campbell</SOC><CITE>2019 ONSC 5899</CITE><PARANUM>36</PARANUM><CORRELAT><CITE>298 A.C.W.S. (3d) 163</CITE></CORRELAT></CASEREF><BOLD>, Respondent's Compendium at Tab 12, p. 124.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>46. The Ontario Court of Appeal confirmed that two requirements must be fulfilled for estoppel to apply in these circumstances:
<P1>(i) there must be knowledge on the part of the insurer of the facts that indic ated a lack of coverage, and</P1>
<P1>(ii) there must be a course of conduct by the insurer upon which the insured relied to its detriment.</P1>
<P1><BOLD><EM>Rosenblood</EM>, <EM>supra</EM> para. 43 at paras. 53-54, RBOA at Tab A6.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>47. The contract of insurance is one that calls for utmost good faith. The details of the use of the dirt bike were clearly alleged in the Statement of Claim. Whether or not it addressed its mind to the matter the insurer must, or should have known, that there was a potential application of an exclusion clause.</P>
<P>48. Silence or inaction will count as a representation if a legal duty shall have been owed by the representor to the representee to make a disclosure, or take steps, the omission of which is relied upon as created the estoppel. Such a relationship exists between an insured and its insurer.</P>
<P>49. Section 131(1)(b) of the <EM>Insurance Act</EM> prevents an insurer from denying coverage under an insurance policy once the insurer has conducted itself in a way that would cause the insured to believe that he was covered. It provides that:
<QUOTE><SEC><N>131.</N><SSEC><N>(1)</N><SSECP>The obligation of an insured to comply with a requirement under a contract is excused to the extent that,
<PARA><N>(b)</N><PARAP>the insurer's conduct reasonably causes the insured to believe that the insured's compliance with the requirement is excused in whole or in part, and the insured acts on that belief to the insured's detriment.</PARAP></PARA></SSECP></SSEC></SEC></QUOTE>
<P1><BOLD><EM>Insurance Act</EM>, RSO 1990, c I.8, s 131(1), RBOA at Tab B1.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>50. Justice MacLeod determined that the Application was launched in August 2016, at the time the Application Record was delivered.</P>
<P>51. Commonwell should be estopped from denying coverage because it knew from a review of the statement of claim, or ought to have known, that Commonwell's Policy excluded coverage in these circumstances, yet defended and continued to defend Campbell.</P>
<P>52. Campbell has been prejudiced by Commonwell's conduct. By commencing and continu ing with the defence, Commonwell has denied Campbell the ability to select counsel of his own choosing, to select the wording of his Statement of Defence, to decline to file a Jury Notice, and to attempt to settle the action at an earlier stage of the litigation. Further, while being defended, he took no further steps to protect his interests, including making further efforts to secure a defence under any other policy of insurance.</P>
<P>53. The Supreme Court of Canada in <CASEREF><SOC>Ryan v Moore</SOC></CASEREF> set out the basis for detrimental reliance:
<QUOTE><P>Detrimental reliance encompasses two distinct, but interrelated, concepts: reliance and detriment. The former requires a finding that the party seeking to establish the estoppel changed his or her course of conduct by acting or abstaining from acting in reliance upon the assumption, <UNDER>thereby altering his or her legal position</UNDER>. If the first step is met, the second requires a finding that, should the other party be allowed to abandon the assumption, detriment will be suffered by the estoppel raiser because of the change from his or her assumed position... (emphasis added)</P></QUOTE>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Ryan v. Moore</SOC><CITE>2005 SCC 38</CITE><PARANUM>69</PARANUM><CORRELAT><CITE>[2005] 2 S.C.R. 53</CITE></CORRELAT></CASEREF><BOLD>., RBOA at Tab A7.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>54. As noted by Professor Bruce MacDougall in <EM>Estoppel</EM>, a leading text on the topic, the loss of opportunity to take some legal steps because of a representation relating to proceedings is a &ldquo;reasonably straightforward detriment, though the legal step would h ave to have made a difference.&rdquo; The author quotes <CASEREF><SOC>McConnell v Aviva Insurance Co of Canada Ltd.</SOC></CASEREF> with respect to this proposition, in which Ross J., of the Alberta Court of Queen's Bench, notes that:
<QUOTE><P>Had [the insured] been advised of a lack of coverage and potential personal exposure, he might have taken a very different approach to the lawsuit, perhaps retaining his own counsel to defend the case and/or negotiating a settlement for a lesser amount that the judgment that has now issued against him.</P></QUOTE>
<P1><BOLD>Bruce MacDougall, <EM>Estoppel</EM>, (Markham: LexisNexis, 2012) at pp. 260-261, RBOA at Tab A8.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>55. At paragraph 40 of his decision, Justice MacLeod determined that in March 2016, when Commonwell first advised Campbell that it was denying coverage, &ldquo;By that time not only had Guarantee denied coverage but the litigation was well advanced.&rdquo;, having earlier found at paragraph 8, &ldquo;It appears the main action had proceeded to the stage of discoveries when Plaintiff's counsel asked defence counsel whether there was any issued abo ut coverage.&rdquo;
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>The Commonwell Mutual Assurance Group v. Campbell</SOC><CITE>2019 ONSC 5899</CITE><PARANUM>40</PARANUM><CORRELAT><CITE>298 A.C.W.S. (3d) 163</CITE></CORRELAT></CASEREF><BOLD>, Respondent's Compendium at Tab 12, p. 124.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>56. At paragraph 62 of its Factum, Commonwell relies on the November 14, 2016 Case Conference Form to state that Justice MacLeod made a palpable and overriding error in inferring that the litigation was well advanced. It is of note that though timelines were created for completion of steps in the litigation, there is nothing in the Form to suggest that the discoveries had not commenced, and/or certain affidavit of documents had been exchanged. What is clear, is that all of these steps, including mediation, were to have been completed well before this matter was heard in May 2018.
<P1><BOLD><EM>Duminy Affidavit</EM> at Exhibit A, Exhibit Book of the Appellant at Tab 3A, pp. 249&ndash;251; Respondent's Compendium at Tab 7, p. 53&ndash;55.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>57. Lastly, prejudice may be presumed if, in the circumstances, the insurer has persisted through steps of the defence. Justice MacLeod turned his mind to this concept at paragraph 37, when he stated:
<QUOTE><P>It has also been held that where the litigation is at an advanced stage, prejudice to the insured is inferred, estoppel applies and in that case there is not need to decide if the actions of the insurer also constitute waiver.</P></QUOTE>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>The Commonwell Mutual Assurance Group v. Campbell</SOC><CITE>2019 ONSC 5899</CITE><PARANUM>37</PARANUM><CORRELAT><CITE>298 A.C.W.S. (3d) 163</CITE></CORRELAT></CASEREF><BOLD>, Respondent's Compendium at Tab 12, p. 124.</BOLD></P1>
<P1><BOLD><EM>Rosenblood</EM>, <EM>supra</EM> para 43. at para. 63, RBOA at Tab A6.</BOLD></P1>
<P1><BOLD><EM>Snair</EM>, <EM>supra</EM> para. 36 at paras 69-70, RBOA at Tab A3.</BOLD></P1>
<P1><BOLD><EM>Western</EM>, <EM>supra</EM> para. 40 at paras. 49&ndash;51, RBOA at Tab A5.</BOLD></P1></P></BLOCK3></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="IV">PART IV&mdash;<UNDER>ADDITIONAL ISSUES RAISED BY CAMPBELL</UNDER></TI>
<BLOCK3><TI><UNDER>Standard of Review</UNDER></TI>
<P>58. Interference in a decision on an application regarding an insurer's duty to defend and indemnify is justified only if the Judge made an error of law, or misapprehended the evidence such that there is an overriding and palpable error. This standard is applicable to Justice MacLeod's factual findings regarding Commonwell's duty to defend and indemnify Campbell.</P>
<P>59. The &ldquo;palpable and overriding&rdquo; standard addresses both the nature of the factual error and its impact on the result.
<QUOTE><P>i. A &ldquo;palpable&rdquo; error is one that is obvious, plain to see or clear. Examples of &ldquo;palpable&rdquo; factual errors include findings made in the complete absence of evidence, findings made in conflict with accepted evidence, findings based on a misapprehension of evidence and findings of fact drawn from primary facts that are the result of speculation.</P>
<P>ii. An &ldquo;overriding&rdquo; error is an error that is sufficiently significant to vitiate the challenged finding(s) of fact. Where the challenged finding of fact is based on a constellation of findings, the conclusion that one or more of those findings is founded on a &ldquo;palpable&rdquo; error does not automatically mean that the error is also &ldquo;overriding&rdquo;. The appellant must demonstrate that the error goes to the root of the challenged finding of fact such that the fact cannot safely stand in the face of that error.</P>
<P>iii. A &ldquo;palpable and overriding error&rdquo; has been interpreted as requiring a decision to be &ldquo;clearly wrong&rdquo; in the sense of being &ldquo;not reasonably supported by the evidence&rdquo;.</P></QUOTE>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Housen v. Nikolaisen</SOC><CITE>2002 SCC 33</CITE><PARANUM>5, 6, 10 and 21</PARANUM><CORRELAT><CITE>[2002] 2 S.C.R. 235</CITE></CORRELAT></CASEREF> <BOLD>[<EM>Housen</EM>], RBOA at Tab A9.</BOLD></P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Waxman v. Waxman</SOC><CITE>2004 CanLlI 39040</CITE><PARANUM>292, 294, 296-297</PARANUM><COURTJUR>Ont. C.A.</COURTJUR><CASEHIST><CASEREF><CITE>[2004] O.J. No. 1765</CITE></CASEREF></CASEHIST></CASEREF><BOLD>, RBOA at Tab A10.</BOLD></P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>L.(H.) v. Canada (Attorney General)</SOC><CITE>2005 SCC 25</CITE><PARANUM>110</PARANUM><CORRELAT><CITE>[2005] 1 S.C.R. 401</CITE></CORRELAT></CASEREF><BOLD>, RBOA at Tab A11.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>60. While it is not disputed that the interpretation of insurance contracts and errors of law are generally reviewed on a standard of correctness, motions regarding an insurer's duty to defe nd are not limited to the interpretation of an insurance contract. Rather, the dominant inquiry on such a motion is the breadth of the pleadings and the nature of the allegations, in which facts must be assumed to be true and the causes of action flowing from those facts must be assessed. Furthermore, this matter also raised the issue of waiver and estoppel.</P>
<P>61. The appropriate standard of review on an appeal of a decision regarding an insurer's duty to defend is a standard of palpable and overriding error. A motion judge's principal focus is:
<QUOTE><P>...not to interpret the terms of the insurance contract, but rather to assess the pleadings in order to ascertain the substance and true nature of the cla im, and whether it could give rise to liability within the policy coverage. In this, Justice Beveridge's Inquiry involved a question of mixed fact and law, and one which was heavily weighted towards the facts. His decision is owed considerable deference. Absent palpable and overriding error we will not intervene...</P></QUOTE>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>ING Insurance Company of Canada v. SREIT (Park West Centre) Ltd.</SOC><CITE>2009 NSCA 38</CITE><PARANUM>19</PARANUM><CORRELAT><CITE>176 A.C.W.S. (3d) 1142</CITE></CORRELAT></CASEREF> <BOLD>[<EM>ING</EM>], RBOA at Tab A12.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>62. Identifying the nature of the judge's error is the first task. An appellate court must identify a crucial flaw in the decision. Doubting the soundness of the judge's findings of fact arising from same, is not a recognized ground of appellate intervention.
<P1><BOLD><EM>ING</EM>, <EM>supra</EM> para. 61 at para 20, RBOA at Tab A12.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>63. An Appellate Court also determines whether the inferences drawn by the judge are reasonably supported by the evidence. If the facts or inferences drawn by the judge are reasonably supported by the evidence, the appellate court cannot reweigh the evidence by substituting, an equally, or even more persuasive conclusion.
<P1><BOLD><EM>Housen</EM>, <EM>supra</EM> para. 59 at paras. 21-22, RBOA at Tab A9.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>64. The Appellant must point to specific errors in the reasons, which justifies the conclusion that the judge failed or improperly considered the evidence or made improper inferences. Commonwell has failed to precisely articulate these errors, if any.
<P1><BOLD><EM>Housen</EM>, <EM>supra</EM> para. 59 at para. 20, RBOA at Tab A9.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>65. Campbell submits that Commonwell's entire factum is a regurgitation of its submissions at first instance and it is seeking a hearing <EM>de novo</EM>.</P></BLOCK3></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="V">PART V&mdash;ORDER REQUESTED</TI>
<P>66. It is respectfully requested that this Honourable Court of Appeal dismiss the within appeal with costs.</P>
<P><BOLD>ALL OF WHICH IS RESPECTFULLY SUBMITTED</BOLD> this 11<SUP>t h</SUP> day of April, 2019.</P>
