<BLOCK1><TI>COSTS SUBMISSIONS OF THE RESPONDENT, SHAYNE CAMPBELL</TI>
<P>1. I n Reasons for Decision dated October 4, 2018, Justice MacLeod dismissed the Application brought by The Commonwell Mutual Assurance Group (&ldquo;Commonwell&rdquo;) against Shayne Campbell. That Application sought a declaration in favour of Commonwell that it is not obliged to provide a defence to Mr. Campbell, and indemnify him, in Court File No. 15-64061. Instead, Justice MacLeod declared that the Commonwell is required to provide Mr. Campbell with defence, indemnify him under its policy of insurance. Pursuant to a Costs Decision dated November 27, 2019, Justice MacLeod ordered that Commonwell pay Mr. Campbell's costs on a substantial indemnity basis.</P>
<P>2. Via this Appeal, Commonwell now seeks to have Justice Macleod's October 4, 2018 Decision set aside.</P>
<P>3. It is submitted that should Mr. Campbell be successful in this Appeal, he should be awarded costs on a <BOLD>full indemnity basis</BOLD>, in the amount of $33,089.68, inclusive of taxes and disbursements. Mr. Campbell's Bill of Costs is attached at <BOLD>Tab A</BOLD> including supporting dockets.</P>
<P>4. This Court has repeatedly affirmed that the basis for awarding costs against an insurer who has unsuccessfully denied coverage is on a full indemnity basis. This entitlement flows directly from the unique nature of the insurance contract which entails a duty to defend at no expense to the insured.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>M.(E.) v Reed</SOC><CITE>[2003] OJ No 1791</CITE><PARANUM>22</PARANUM><COURTJUR>C.A</COURTJUR></CASEREF><BOLD>. [Tab B]</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>5. As illustration, the Court of Appeal in <CASEREF><SOC>Godonoaga (Litigation Guardian of) v Khatambakhsh</SOC><YEAR>2000</YEAR></CASEREF>, noted that:
<QUOTE><P>The appellants were entitled to a defence by their insurer without expense to them. Accordingly, that matter now having been determined in their favour, they should have their costs on a solicitor and his own client's scale for the defence of the main action and cross-claims until such time as the respondent insurer serves and files a notice of change of solicitors and takes over the insurers' defence. Such costs would include the conduct of the third-party proceedings and the motion before (the motion judge) and this appeal.</P></QUOTE>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Godonoaga (Litigation Guardian of) v Khatambakhsh</SOC><CITE>2000 CanLII 16891</CITE><CORRELAT><CITE>50 OR (3d) 417</CITE><PARANUM>4</PARANUM></CORRELAT><COURTJUR>C.A</COURTJUR></CASEREF><BOLD>. [Tab C]</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>6. Mr. Campbell further submits that the amount of $33,089.68 is reasonable in view of the factors listed in Rule 57 of the <EM>Rules of Civil Procedure</EM>.</P>
<P>7. Success in this Appeal was crucial to Mr. Campbell because the Plaintiff in the underlying accident suffered a catastrophic injury and is alleging damages in excess of $3,000,000. If Mr. Campbell were not to have been successful in response to the Application or this Appeal, he would have been personally liable for any awards made against him in the underlying action (Subrule 57.01(1)(d)).</P>
<P>8. Christine Powell has been practicing litigation, principally in the area of insurance law, since 2000. Given her experience, her hourly rate of $375 is appropriate in the Ottawa market. Attempts to minimize costs were extensive, in that law clerks and articling students were utilized for more routine tasks where possible (Subrule 57.01(1)(0.a)).</P>
<P>9. It is recognized that as a general rule, a successful party is entitled to costs of the Appeal and of the decision below. However, this Honourable Court has complete discretion in the matter of costs and may mould its order so as to do justice. Given Commonwell's position and the $3,000,000.00 being claimed in the underlying action, it is understandable that Campbell had no choice but to resist this Application. Should Commonwell prove successful on this Appeal, it is undeniable that Campbell will be faced with significant financial hardship, regardless of whether or not h is defence of the underlying action proves successful. It is therefore respectfully submitted that in the event that Commonwell is found successful on this Appeal, this Honourable Court should exercise its discretion, order no costs for this Appeal, and allow Justice MacLeod's November 27<SUP>th</SUP> Costs Decision to stand.</P>
<P>ALL OF WHICH IS RESPECTFULLY SUBMITTED this 16 day of August, 2019.</P>
<P>&ellip35; Christine A. Powell</P></BLOCK1>
